Plant material innovation at Land Grant Universities

Intellectural property protections and matieral licensing, 1980-2020

Liza Wood, Adam Vera, Victoria Fletcher

2022-10-05

This page summarizes plant breeding activities at US Land Grant Universities (LGUs) and the subsequent trends in technology transfer between universities and companies. Data for these summaries are combined across four sources:
1. PVP database 2. USPTO database
3. Licensing metadata from 25 LGUs, collected via FOIA requests
4. Company data collected from the D&B Hoovers database

How have LGUs been protecting their plant material?

The PVP and USPTO databases were scraped and automated text matching was used to identify applications by the 50 1862 LGUs. For PVPs, this meant looking for applications with Universities as Applicants, and for USPTO, this meant looking for LGUs as Assignees, as well as ??.

Between 1980-2020 2366 applications have been submitted by LGUs, 1872 as PVP and 806 as USPTO (0 as plant patents and 0 as utility patents). There have a steady increase in both IP types over time:

What qualities do these plants have?

Of the 2366 plant varieties that have been protected by PVPs or patents, we qualitatively coded a random subset of the plant descriptions (10%, 236.6). Coding resulted in the identification of X themes: [TO FILL IN]. We used this 10% to train a neural network to classify plant description text into these categories, which is X% effective. Technology transfer: What happens to these varieties?

Beyond protecting material, universities license the plant material they develop some of it protected, others not to third parties to commercialize and/or continue to innovation. I collected records of licensing data between 2000-2020 for 25 LGUs.

Preliminary look at these data include the following features:

  • 7610 licensing agreements across 25 Land Grant Universities between 2000-2020
  • Agreements are with 1098 companies and 134 other entities (organizations, universities, individuals, etc.)
  • 1865 unique plant varieties and/or breeding lines are licensed, which accounts for about 30.2% of the plant protections granted during roughly that same time (1995-2020).
  • These plant varieties span 11 different crop categories, including: Non-food (cotton & tabacco), Fruits & nuts, Cereals, Roots & tubers, Vegetables & melons, Ornamental, Grasses & fodder, Oilseeds, Leguminous, Sugar, spice & medicinal, NA

Where is material being distributed?

Summaries over time

This varies by state considerably. The number of licenses over the twenty year periods ranges from only 1 in Arizona, Rhode Island to 2401 in Washington, with an annual average of 22 licenses. Below are the number of licenses for each state over time, with the y axis cut at 100.

ggplot(df, aes(x = license_yr)) +
  geom_bar() +
  #geom_text(tab, aes(x = x, label = n)) + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Count", title = "Licenses over time by state") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  facet_wrap(~uni_state, nrow = 5) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0,100)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

df %>% 
  group_by(crop_cat) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  mutate(crop_cat = factor(crop_cat, levels = .$crop_cat)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = crop_cat, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  stat_identity(geom = "text", colour = "white", size = 2,
                aes(label = n),
                position=position_stack(vjust=0.5)) +
  labs(x = "", y = "Count", title = "Plant licensing by crop category") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 10),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

df %>% 
  group_by(license_yr, crop_cat) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(license_yr) %>% 
  mutate(yr_n = sum(n)) %>% 
  mutate(prop = round(100*n/yr_n, 0)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = license_yr, y = n, color = crop_cat)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Count", color = "Crop",
       title = "Number of licenses by crop category over time") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Spectral") +
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.1, size = 10)) 

df %>% 
  mutate(spatial_match = case_when(
    spatial_match == "Outside region" ~ "Extra-regional",
    spatial_match == "Within region" ~ "Regional",
    T ~ spatial_match)) %>% 
  group_by(license_yr, spatial_match) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(license_yr) %>% 
  mutate(yr_n = sum(n)) %>% 
  mutate(prop = round(100*n/yr_n, 0)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = license_yr, y = prop, fill = spatial_match)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  stat_identity(geom = "text", colour = "white", size = 3.5,
                aes(label = prop),
                position=position_stack(vjust=0.5)) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Percent", fill = "Licensee location",
       title = "Percent of licenses by licensee over time") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors9[c(2,3,8)])+
  theme_linedraw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 10))
